ACT V. ScENE IV.

Parmeno comes walking along by himself, happy in the imagined success of his plot. He recounts the many advantages that must arise from it to Chaerea, and the great glory that will redound to the contriver. All these sanguine hopes, this whole solemnity of prepara- tion, paves the way for his heavier distress, when Pythias informs him of the il] success of it, for he is seen to fall from the highest expecta- tions into an abyss of despair; and so great is his fright, that he is driven to make a discovery to the' old man, which he foresaw would bring vengeance upon himself.
